Polyfill C23 UINTPTR_WIDTH / UCHAR_WIDTH inside lib/rawmemchr.c for MSVC.

gnulib's lib/rawmemchr.c uses C23's UINTPTR_WIDTH and UCHAR_WIDTH in a
static_assert.  On Linux/macOS the generated lib/stdint.h / lib/limits.h
polyfill these via gnulib's templates; on MSVC the gnulib stdint
template mis-parses there (we deliberately skip generating it -- see the
BUILD.bazel comment on lib_hdrs_nonmsvc), and the MSVC SDK does not
define the macros either, leading to C2065/C2057 errors.

Define both macros directly in rawmemchr.c as constant expressions in
terms of CHAR_BIT (from <limits.h>) and sizeof (uintptr_t).  Guarded by
`#ifndef` so platforms with the real C23 macros are unaffected.

--- a/lib/rawmemchr.c
+++ b/lib/rawmemchr.c
@@ -43,6 +43,14 @@
 
   /* You can change this typedef to experiment with performance.  */
   typedef uintptr_t longword;
+  /* MSVC's <stdint.h>/<limits.h> don't yet define these C23 macros; the
+     equivalents below are constant expressions valid in static_assert.  */
+# ifndef UINTPTR_WIDTH
+#  define UINTPTR_WIDTH (sizeof (uintptr_t) * CHAR_BIT)
+# endif
+# ifndef UCHAR_WIDTH
+#  define UCHAR_WIDTH CHAR_BIT
+# endif
   /* Verify that the longword type lacks padding bits.  */
   static_assert (UINTPTR_WIDTH == UCHAR_WIDTH * sizeof (uintptr_t));
 
